Cybersecurity is about protecting digital systems and data.

1. One simple model is the CIA Triad:

ğŸ”¹Confidentiality â†’ Only the right people should see the data. Example: your bank balance should be private.
ğŸ”¹Integrity â†’ Data should not be changed without permission. Example: a hacker should not change marks in a university database.
ğŸ”¹Availability â†’ Systems should be up and working when needed. Example: ATMs must work 24/7.


2. Common Threats

ğŸ”¹Phishing â†’ fake emails/websites to steal your password.
ğŸ”¹Malware â†’ viruses or trojans that harm your system.
ğŸ”¹Ransomware â†’ locks your files and asks for money.
ğŸ”¹Brute-force attack â†’ trying many passwords until one works.
ğŸ”¹SQL Injection â†’ inserting malicious queries into a websiteâ€™s database.
ğŸ”¹DDoS â†’ flooding a website with traffic to make it crash.


3.Attack Vectors (Ways Hackers Attack)
ğŸ”¹Social Engineering â†’ Tricking people instead of systems.
  Examples: phishing emails, fake IT calls, malicious USBs.
ğŸ”¹Wireless Attacks â†’ Targeting Wi-Fi or Bluetooth.
  Examples: cracking weak Wi-Fi passwords, fake hotspots, packet sniffing.
ğŸ”¹Insider Threats â†’ Misuse of access by employees/contractors.
  Examples: stealing data, weak password habits, or compromised accounts.


4.ğŸŒ Networking Basics

    ğŸ”¹OSI Model (Open Systems Interconnection)
     .The OSI model explains how data travels from one computer to another in 7 layers. Think of it like a postal system â€” from writing a letter to delivering it.
        1.Physical Layer â†’ cables, Wi-Fi, signals. Example: Ethernet cable or Wi-Fi radio.
        2.Data Link Layer â†’ organizes data into frames, handles MAC addresses. Example: Switches, ARP.
        3.Network Layer â†’ routes data using IP addresses. Example: Routers, IPv4/IPv6.
        4.Transport Layer â†’ ensures reliable delivery with TCP/UDP. Example: TCP (guaranteed), UDP (faster, no guarantee).
        5.Session Layer â†’ manages communication sessions. Example: keeping you logged into a website.
        6.Presentation Layer â†’ formats and encrypts data. Example: SSL/TLS encryption.
        7.Application Layer â†’ what the user interacts with. Example: Browser (HTTP/HTTPS), Email (SMTP).

  
   ğŸ”¹TCP/IP Model
    .The TCP/IP model is a simpler, practical version of OSI with 4 layers. This is what the internet actually uses.
      1.Application Layer â†’ user apps like web (HTTP), email (SMTP).
      2.Transport Layer â†’ manages connections (TCP = reliable, UDP = fast).
      3.Internet Layer â†’ routes data using IP addresses.
      4.Network Access Layer â†’ physical sending of data (Ethernet, Wi-Fi).


   ğŸ”¹DNS (Domain Name System)

        .DNS = Domain Name System â†’ the phonebook of the internet.
        .Humans use names like google.com.
        .Computers need numbers (IP addresses, e.g., 142.250.182.14).
        .DNS converts names â†’ IPs.


  ğŸ”¹HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)

        .Standard protocol for web communication.
        .Sends data in plain text â†’ anyone can read it if intercepted.
        .Example: Login credentials sent via HTTP can be stolen with packet sniffers.


  ğŸ”¹HTTPS (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure)

        .HTTP + SSL/TLS encryption.
        .Encrypts communication â†’ attackers canâ€™t read your data.
        .Uses certificates to prove website authenticity.
        .Example: Banking, Gmail, Facebook all use HTTPS.


  ğŸ”¹IP Addressing

      .An IP address is like a home address for devices in a network.
        1.IPv4 â†’ most common, looks like 192.168.1.1.
        2.IPv6 â†’ newer, longer, looks like 2001:0db8:85a3::8a2e:0370:7334.  

      .Classes of IPv4:
        a.Class A: 1.0.0.0 â€“ 126.255.255.255 (large networks) 
        b.Class B: 128.0.0.0 â€“ 191.255.255.255 (medium) 
        c.Class C: 192.0.0.0 â€“ 223.255.255.255 (small networks, home Wi-Fi)

      .Private IP Ranges (used inside LANs, not public internet)
        a.Class A: 10.0.0.0 â€“ 10.255.255.255
        b.Class B: 172.16.0.0 â€“ 172.31.255.255 
        c.Class C: 192.168.0.0 â€“ 192.168.255.255



  ğŸ”¹Subnetting

      .Subnetting = dividing a large network into smaller parts.
       Itâ€™s like dividing a big apartment building into smaller flats.

          .Example:
            .IP: 192.168.1.10
            .Subnet Mask: 255.255.255.0 â†’ /24

          .Meaning:
            .First 3 octets (192.168.1) = Network part.
            .Last octet (.10) = Host part (device number).
          .This /24 network can have 254 devices (1â€“254 usable addresses).



  ğŸ”¹ What is NAT?

      .NAT = Network Address Translation.
      .Itâ€™s used in routers to let many devices in a private network (like your home Wi-Fi) share one public IP address on the internet.
      .IPv4 addresses are limited â†’ NAT helps reuse private addresses.
      .Provides a layer of security (outside world canâ€™t directly see your private devices).

      .Types of NAT

        .Static NAT â€“ One private IP â†” One public IP (fixed mapping).
        .Dynamic NAT â€“ Private IP â†” Public IP from a pool (changes).
        .PAT (Port Address Translation) aka NAT Overload â€“ Many private IPs share one public IP using different ports (most common in homes).

      .In short:
        .NAT = your router acting like a translator.
        .It hides private IPs and lets multiple devices share the same public IP.



5.Cryptography Basics

  ğŸ”¹Symmetric Encryption

    What it is: Uses one key to both lock (encrypt) and unlock (decrypt) the data.
    Example: Locking a diary with a single key; the same key opens it.
    Pros: Fast and simple.
    Cons: Both sender and receiver must share the key secretly, which can be risky.
    Common examples: AES, DES, RC4

  ğŸ”¹Asymmetric Encryption

    What it is: Uses two keys â€” a public key to encrypt and a private key to decrypt.
    Example: You send a locked box to a friend; only your friend has the key to open it.
    Pros: No need to share private keys; safer for communication.
    Cons: Slower than symmetric encryption.
    Common examples: RSA, ECC

ğŸ’¡ Quick way to remember:
     Symmetric = Same key
     Asymmetric = Different keys


    ğŸ”¹What is Hashing?

    Hashing = taking some data (like a password, file, or text) â†’ running it through a math formula â†’ getting a fixed-length code (called a hash).
    Same input â†’ always same hash.
    Small change in input â†’ totally different hash.
    Hashes canâ€™t be easily reversed back to the original data.

    ğŸ”¹ MD5

      Old hashing algorithm.
      Output: 32 characters (128 bits).
      Example: hello â†’ 5d41402abc4b2a76b9719d911017c592.
      Problem: Itâ€™s broken (hackers can crack it). Not safe for passwords.

    ğŸ”¹ SHA-256
      A newer and stronger hashing algorithm (part of the SHA-2 family).
      Output: 64 characters (256 bits).
      Example: hello â†’ 2cf24dba5... (much longer).
      Secure and widely used (Bitcoin, SSL, file integrity).

    ğŸ‘‰ In short:
      MD5 = fast but weak (donâ€™t use for security).
      SHA-256 = slower but much stronger (safe for modern use).


    ğŸ”¹ What is a Digital Certificate?

      .Think of it like an online ID card for websites.
      .Issued by a trusted company called a Certificate Authority (CA).
      .It proves:
        1.The website is real (not fake).
        2.It owns the correct encryption keys.

    ğŸ”¹ What is SSL/TLS?
      
      .SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) and TLS (Transport Layer Security) are security protocols.
      .They make sure that when you visit a website, the data between your browser and the server is encrypted (safe from hackers).
      .Example: When you see https:// with a ğŸ”’ lock in the browser, itâ€™s using SSL/TLS.


    ğŸ”¹ Encrypt & Decrypt with OpenSSL

      .Encrypt a file:
        openssl enc -aes-256-cbc -salt -in message.txt -out message.enc
      .Decrypt a file:
        openssl enc -d -aes-256-cbc -in message.enc -out message_decrypted.txt
      .Encrypt text (Base64):
        echo "SecretMessage123" | openssl enc -aes-256-cbc -a -salt -pass pass:mypassword
      .Decrypt text (Base64):
        echo "<encrypted_text_here>" | openssl enc -aes-256-cbc -a -d -pass pass:mypassword

        -aes-256-cbc = algorithm
        -d = decrypt
        -a = base64 encoding
        -pass pass: = password for quick testing


 ğŸ”¹CHEAT-SHEET

    1.File & Directory
      pwd             # show current directory
      ls              # list files
      ls -l           # list with details
      cd dir_name     # change directory
      cd ..           # go back one level
      mkdir new_dir   # make directory
      rmdir old_dir   # remove empty directory


    2.File Operations
      touch file.txt       # create empty file
      cp file1 file2       # copy file
      mv file1 file2       # move/rename file
      rm file.txt          # delete file
      cat file.txt         # show file content
      nano file.txt        # edit file (nano editor)


    3.Permissions
      ls -l                # check permissions
      chmod 755 file.txt   # change permissions
      chown user file.txt  # change owner


    4.System Info
      whoami          # current user
      uname -a        # system info
      df -h           # disk usage
      free -h         # memory usage
      top             # running processes


    5.Package Management
      sudo apt update          # update repo list
      sudo apt upgrade         # upgrade packages
      sudo apt install pkg     # install package
      sudo apt remove pkg      # remove package


    6.Networking
      ifconfig / ip a    # show IP addresses
      ping google.com    # test connectivity
      curl example.com   # get webpage


    7.Others
      history       # show command history
      clear         # clear terminal
      man command   # help for command









